III. MINN. STAT. §518.175 SUBD. 1 (g) FAILS STRICT SCRUTINY BECAUSE
LESS RESTRICTIVE MEANS ARE AVAILABLE 4
State action that implicates a fundamental right cannot justify itself simply on the
basis of serving a “compelling state interest.” Instead, the state must show its implication
of a fundamental right both serves a compelling state interest and is narrowly tailored.
The narrow tailoring requirement insists that infringements of protected rights
must be necessary in order to be justified.5 The Supreme Court sometimes expresses
essentially the same demand when it says that the government's chosen means must be
"the least restrictive alternative" that would achieve its goals.6 A law would not be
necessary to achieve its ends if the government could accomplish the same result while
inflicting lesser burdens on protected rights.7
7 The necessity or narrow tailoring requirement may explain why the Supreme Court has demanded that a
government body explore race-neutral alternatives before implementing an affirmative action plan. At least one
prominent commentator has expressed puzzlement about this requirement: "The Court's preference for 'race-neutral
means to increase minority participation' is inconsistent with narrow tailoring" because "[e]xtending affirmative
action subsidies to non-victim whites produces less-tailored, over-inclusive programs." Ayres, supra note 322, at
1784. If this criticism fails, it must be because the Court believes that a race-neutral program would not infringe any
triggering right at all and, accordingly, that infringement is not necessary for the government to accomplish its
compelling goal. This is of course a controversial conclusion in view of the Court's suggestion in Washington v.
Davis, 426 U.S. 229 (1976), that a facially neutral statute adopted for racially discriminatory reasons would trigger
strict judicial scrutiny. See id. at 241-42. So far, however, the Court has never held or had occasion to hold that a
6 Ashcroft v. ACLU, 542 U.S. at 666; Playboy, 529 U.S. at 815; Sable Commc'ns, 492 U.S. at 126; see Fla. Star v.
B.J.F., 491 U.S. 524, 538 (1989) (striking down a governmental action in part because less speech-restrictive
alternatives were available); Volokh, supra note 322, at 2422.
5 See, e.g., Republican Party of Minn. v. White, 536 U.S. 765, 775 (2002) ("[Tlo show that the [statute] is narrowly
tailored, [the government] must demonstrate that it does not 'unnecessarily circumscrib[e] protected expression.'
(fourth alteration in original) (quoting Brown v. Hartlage, 456 U.S. 45, 54 (1982))); Kramer v. Union Free Sch. Dist.
No. 15, 395 U.S. 621, 632 (1969) ("[T]he classifications must be tailored so that the exclusion of appellant and
members of his class is necessary to achieve the articulated state goal.").
4 For the purposes of this brief, the protection of children is a non-disputed “compelling state interest.”See Denver
Area Educ. Telecomms. Consortium, Inc. v. FCC, 518 U.S. 727, 755 (1996) (plurality opinion) ("We agree with the
Government that protection of children is a 'compelling interest."'). See, e.g., Ashcroft v. ACLU, 542 U.S. at 689
(Breyer, J., dissenting) (finding that protecting children from commercial pornography is a compelling governmental
interest); Denver Area Educ. Telecomms. Consortium, Inc. v. FCC, 518 U.S. 727, 755 (1996) (plurality opinion)
("We agree with the Government that protection of children is a 'compelling interest."'); Sable Commc'ns v. FCC,
492 U.S. 115, 126 (1989) ("We have recognized that there is a compelling interest in protecting the physical and
psychological well-being of minors.").
7
Here, the State cannot show Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) is narrowly tailored;
nor can the State show Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) is legislating using the least
restrictive means. Articulating the same standard differently, the State cannot carry its
burden to show Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) is necessary to achieve a “compelling
state interest.”
First, this analysis begs the question: what is the compelling state interest
undergirding Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g)? However vague, the undisputed purpose
of this statute is to effectuate the “best interests of the child.” The statutory regime itself
doesn’t announce the purpose explicitly, but in context—specifically in light of Minn.
Stat. §518.17—this is the clear and demonstrated intent of the statute.
Second, the key question is one of narrow-tailoring: what less restrictive
alternatives equally advance the government's interest in serving the best interests of the
children? If less restrictive alternatives exist, then Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) is
unconstitutional.
First, it’s analytically necessary to underscore what and precisely how Minn. Stat.
§ 518.175 Subd. 1(g) restricts. These are two separate inquiries, each easily explicated.
First, regarding what is restricted: Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) restricts
parenting time. More specifically, it restricts the rebuttable presumption of parenting
time. That is, during a divorce or custody action, this statute allocates the time a parent
will spend with his or her child(ren).
facially race-neutral affirmative action plan would trigger the same strict judicial scrutiny as a facially race-based
affirmative action plan.
8
Second, regarding how restriction is occurring, Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g)
sets a (rebuttable) presumptive minimum parenting time at 25%. As a percentage, this
restriction is quantitative. As a quantitative value (percentage), comparison to other
regimes is made particularly easy. That is, an analysis can compare a 25% presumption to
a 50% presumption, for example, because they are both numerical values.
This analysis now turns to the task of identifying and examining whether and
what less restrictive alternatives exist. This task is decidedly not difficult.
Consider a 26% rebuttable presumption of parenting time, for example. Or, a 27%
presumption. Or, a 50% presumption.
If any one of these alternatives accomplishes the stated “compelling interest” of
serving a child’s best interests, then the 25% presumption is not, by definition, the least
restrictive statutory regime.
Additionally, it’s essential to point out, per the requirements of strict scrutiny, the
State bears the burden of showing the 25% presumption is the least restrictive means—a
task which cannot be performed.
Our analysis will begin with the 50% presumption. A 50% presumption means,
upon dissolution or separation, parents would each receive equal parenting time,
consistent with and not burdening their fundamental rights as parents. This—a 50%
presumption— is the least restrictive means for at least three reasons.
First, consider a narrow-tailoring analysis. In other words, let’s perform the math.
A 50% presumption offers 25% more parenting time than a 25% presumption. The
9
question is whether or not it achieves the same goal. What goal? The goal of serving the
best interests of the child. If the 25% and 50% presumption equally achieve this goal, the
50% is less restrictive and, therefore, Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) is
unconstitutional.
The 50% presumption not only equally achieves this goal of effectuating the best
interests of the child, it outperforms the 25% presumption. The research unequivocally
confirms that more equal parenting yields more positive outcomes for children. For
example, studies show:
● Children living in shared custody are less stressed than their counterparts who live
full-time with one parent8
;
● Preschool children aged 3 to 5 in joint physical custody have fewer psychological
problems than those who live mostly or only with one parent9
; and
● Adolescents in shared parenting families make better grades, are less depressed, and are
more well-adjusted behaviorally than adolescents who live primarily with their mother10
● Adolescents in shared parenting families score better in measures of depression, anxiety,
substance use, antisocial behavior, truancy, cheating, and delinquency than those other
children of divorce.11
● Adolescents in shared parenting families are less likely to be stressed by the need to take
care of their mother.
