The research is clear: equal and shared parenting is far, far, far better for children than unequal
parenting time. In other words, a child’s best interests (absent findings akin to abuse or
endangerment) requires a 50% parenting presumption, not a 25% presumption. It’s instructive to,
if only briefly, to examine the primary reason why this is the case.
A 50% presumption is in the best interests of children (and their parents) for many
reasons. First, since joint custody treats both parents as equals, rather than as victor and
vanquished, joint custodial parents tend to treat each other with more respect and less
resentment. Meanwhile, 50% of their counterparts in sole custody situations actively try to
sabotage the other party’s relationship with their children.20 Second, biology favors shared and
equal joint parenting.21 That is, the beneficial effects of dual parent contact begin from the time a
child is born. The more frequently a father visits a prematurely born infant, for example, the
more rapidly the child gains needed weight and becomes healthier, and the better the infant’s
21Levy-Shiff, R., et. al., Fathers’ Hospital Visits to their Preterm Infants as a Predictor of Father-Infant Relationship
and Infant Development, 86 PEDIATRICS 291-92 (1990). By the age of 6 months, the more interaction a boy has
with both parents, the higher his mental competence and psychomotor functionality, and the more trust and verbal
openness he displays. Pederson, Rubenstein and Yarrow, supra; Yarrow, L.J., et. al, Cognitive and Motivational
Development in Early Childhood, in B. Z. Friedlander, et. al., 3 EXCEPTIONAL INFANT (1974). The overall
adjustment of children of all ages--of joint custodians is similar to that of children in happy, intact families. Pojman,
E.G., Emotional Adjustment of Boys in Sole Custody and Joint Custody Compared with Adjustment of Boys in
Happy and Unhappy Marriages, doctoral dissertation, California Graduate Institute, Los Angeles, Calif. (1982).
20 Wallerstein, J. and Kelly, J., SURVIVING THE BREAKUP (1980), at 125.
