Having established that equal and shared parenting is far, far, far better for children than
unequal parenting time, this means that a 25% presumption is less effective at achieving the
stated aim of protecting children than a 50% presumption. This means that a 25% presumption is
less effective at achieving the stated aim of protecting children than a 50% presumption.
Moreover, not only does a 50% presumption of parenting time better serve children, it does not
trample a parent’s fundamental right.
Here, at this juncture, the analysis may grind to a halt. The research is clear. There is no
door through which Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g can walk through and survive constitutional
muster.
That is, a 50% rebuttable parenting time presumption not only equally achieves this goal
of effectuating the best interests of the child, it outperforms the 25% presumption in the arena of
a child’s best interests.
In other words, the State fails the least-restrictive means test because of the following
basic math: a 50% presumption yields better outcomes and is less restrictive than a 25%
presumption.
In order to strike down Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g), that’s the only calculation that
must be made. To be even more precise: a 50% presumption is the least restrictive means
possible, and the most most beneficial to children and parents along multiple metrics.
parents who are involved in a sole-custody- with-visitation arrangement. Willenz, Pam, bChildren likely to be better
adjusted in joint vs. sole custody arrangements in most cases, according to review of research,c Press Release, Am.
Psychological Assoc. Public Affairs Office (March, 2002). This makes sense, given that it is only the sole custody
arrangement that requires one parent to be the winner and the other parent the loser. It also stands to reason that this
would be the case because joint custody enables a shift of focus from oneVs own interests to those of oneVs child,
thereby encouraging mature behavior and discouraging divisive, childish conflict. Potash, Marlin S., Psychological
Support for a Rebuttable Presumption of Joint Custody, 4 PROB. L. J. 17 (1982).
14
Additionally, and intriguingly, the Supreme Court has already made this very same
pronouncement: stating that a 25% presumption is antithetical to the stated goal of serving the
child’s best interests.
The State registers no gain towards its declared goals when it separates children
from the custody of fit parents. Santosky v. Kramer, 455 US 745, 766-67
(1982)(emphasis added).
“No gain” is absolute language, free of ambiguity. Santosky stands for the proposition
that: “No gain” is registered when the state “separates children from the custody of fit
parents.” Id. Here, Minn. Stat. §518.175 does precisely that: “separates children from the
custody of fit parents.” That is, without requiring a showing that a parent is not “fit,” the
Statute only guarantees a rebuttable presumption of 25% parenting time. This separates
children from the custody of fit parents. And, according to Santosky, the result is “no
gain.”
THEREFORE, THE ONLY CUSTODIAL DETERMINATION FOR TWO FIT
PARENTS, IS EQUAL 50-50 REBUTTABLE CUSTODY PRESUMPTION. THIS
SURVIVES “STRICT SCRUTINY,” DOES NOT VIOLATE DUE PROCESS, AND IS IN
THE “BEST INTERESTS OF THE CHILD”
Because the Minnesota statutory regime embodied in § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) only
establishes a presumption of 25% parenting time, it does not adequately protect a parent’s
opportunity to form a relationship with his child.
To the contrary, the statute peremptorily deprives fundamental parental rights without a
determination of unfitness as a parent. As such, the statutory scheme violates the Due Process
clause. Lehr, supra at 262-63.
15
As the Stanley Court put it, “Procedure by presumption is always cheaper and easier than
individualized determination…” but the Constitution recognizes higher values than speed and
efficiency. Stanley, supra, 405 U.S. at 656-657.
CONCLUSION
In conclusion, the Court’s authority to strike down this statute as unconstitutional is a part
of a “solemn duty” to bring statutes into constitutional compliance, as the court noted in Mugler
v. Kansas, 123 U.S. 623, 661 (1887);
“It belongs to [the legislature]... to determine, primarily, what measures are appropriate or
needful for the protection of the public morals, the public health, or the public safety...
There are, of necessity, limits beyond which legislation cannot rightfully go. While every
possible presumption is to be indulged in favor of the validity of a statute, (Sinking Fund
Cases, 99 U.S. 718 ,) the courts must obey the constitution rather than the
law-making department of government, and must, upon their own responsibility,
determine whether, in any particular case, these limits have been passed.”
This Petitioner urges the Court to obey the mandates of the Constitution. This Petitioner urges
the Court to protect the sacred right of parents. This Petitioner urges the Court to act in the best
interests of children—and parents alike. By every measure, the research indicates that joint and
equal shared parenting is in the best interests of the child.
For the reasons stated herein, Petitioner respectfully requests that Minn. Stat. § 518.175
Subd. 1(g be declared unconstitutional.
Minn. Stat. § 518.175 Subd. 1(g) is unconstitutional on its face insofar as it violates the
Due Process clause of the Fourteenth Amendment. As such, the statutory language should be
amended to reflect a rebuttable presumption of shared and equal parenting time. Specifically,
“25%” should be stricken and replaced with “50%”
